  mk("During an active bioterrorism event with suspected anthrax exposure, what post-exposure prophylaxis should the emergency nurse expect to distribute?",
    ["Ciprofloxacin 500 mg PO BID or doxycycline 100 mg PO BID for 60 days for exposed individuals, combined with anthrax vaccine if available; prophylaxis should begin immediately without waiting for culture confirmation", "No prophylaxis is available for anthrax exposure", "Prophylaxis only after positive culture results", "Amoxicillin as the sole first-line agent"],
    0, "Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) for anthrax (Bacillus anthracis) follows CDC and WHO guidelines: (1) First-line agents: Ciprofloxacin 500 mg PO BID or Doxycycline 100 mg PO BID; both are effective against anthrax and are available in the Strategic National Stockpile (SNS); (2) Duration: 60 days (anthrax spores can remain dormant in the lungs for weeks before germinating); (3) Anthrax vaccine: if available, 3-dose series (0, 2, 4 weeks) in combination with antibiotics may allow shortening of antibiotic course; (4) Timing: PEP should begin IMMEDIATELY upon suspected exposure; do not wait for culture confirmation as inhaled anthrax has nearly 100% mortality once symptoms develop; (5) Mass prophylaxis: FDA Emergency Use Authorization may allow expanded distribution; Points of Dispensing (PODs) established for community-wide distribution; Strategic National Stockpile assets deployed within 12 hours; (6) Special populations: ciprofloxacin is the preferred agent for pregnant women and children in a mass exposure event despite usual age/pregnancy concerns, because the benefit of anthrax prevention outweighs the risks. Amoxicillin is a third-line agent used only after susceptibility testing confirms effectiveness.", "Distribute ciprofloxacin or doxycycline for 60 days as anthrax post-exposure prophylaxis, initiating immediately without waiting for culture confirmation", "Chemical/Biological/Radiological/Nuclear (CBRN) Response", 3, "recall",
    "Anthrax PEP: cipro or doxycycline for 60 DAYS immediately; do not wait for cultures. SNS deployed within 12 hours for mass prophylaxis",
    ["Cipro 500 mg BID or doxy 100 mg BID for 60 days", "Begin immediately; inhaled anthrax nearly 100% fatal if symptomatic", "SNS assets deployed within 12 hours", "Cipro preferred even in pregnancy/children for mass exposure"],
    "Delayed PEP for anthrax exposure can be fatal; once symptoms develop, inhaled anthrax has near 100% mortality even with treatment",
    ["Effective prophylaxis exists and is available in the SNS", "Waiting for cultures allows spore germination and disease development", "Amoxicillin is third-line after susceptibility testing, not first-line"],
    "cbrn-response");

  mk("A nurse is managing shelter operations when severe weather warnings indicate a tornado is approaching the shelter location. What immediate protective actions should be implemented?",
    ["Move all shelter occupants to interior rooms on the lowest floor, away from windows and exterior walls; protect heads with available materials; maintain accountability of all occupants; prepare first aid supplies for potential injuries", "Evacuate the shelter completely", "Open all windows to equalize pressure", "Continue normal shelter operations"],
    0, "Tornado protective actions for shelter populations: (1) IMMEDIATE: move all occupants to interior rooms on the lowest floor of the structure; below ground (basement) is ideal; (2) Position: away from windows, exterior walls, and large open rooms (gymnasiums have roof failure risk); crouch low, cover head and neck with arms or available materials (mattresses, blankets, pillows); (3) Accountability: maintain roll call of all shelter occupants; note locations of mobility-limited individuals who may need assistance; (4) Communication: activate NOAA weather radio; monitor local emergency broadcast; notify emergency management of shelter location and population; (5) Medical preparation: stage first aid supplies near the safe area; anticipate injuries from structural collapse, flying debris, lacerations, and crush injuries; (6) Special needs: ensure medical equipment (oxygen, wheelchairs) is moved with patients who need them; account for pediatric populations; (7) Post-storm: do not move occupants until all-clear is received; assess structure for safety before resuming normal operations; watch for downed power lines and gas leaks. Opening windows is a myth that wastes critical time.", "Implement tornado protective actions in disaster shelters including interior positioning, head protection, accountability, and medical preparedness for blast injuries", "Blast Injury Patterns", 2, "application",
    "Interior rooms, lowest floor, away from windows; opening windows is a MYTH that wastes time; gymnasiums have high roof failure risk during tornadoes",
    ["Interior rooms, lowest floor, below ground if possible", "Away from windows, exterior walls, and gymnasiums", "Protect head and neck with available materials", "Opening windows is a myth; wastes critical protection time"],
    "Tornado warning with a shelter full of vulnerable people is a life-threatening emergency; seconds matter in getting people to safe positions",
    ["Evacuation to outdoors during an approaching tornado increases danger", "Opening windows does not equalize pressure and wastes time", "Continuing normal operations ignores an immediate life threat"],
    "blast-injury-patterns");

